fields.text_one: Willie smiled, his cheeks burning ______ excitement.
fields.explanation: If you are burning with a particular feeling, you feel it very strongly

fields.text_one: She'd fallen asleep in her chair and the fire had burnt ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to stop burning because there is nothing left for it to burn"

fields.text_one: After the war, he bought ______ his brother Bill 's interest in the machine shop.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to buy someone’s share of a business or property that you previously owned together, so that you own all of it"

fields.text_one: People are buying _____ stocks of food in case the storm hits their area.

fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to spend time somewhere not doing anything, for example because you have nothing to do, or because you are waiting for something or someone.

fields.text_one: It’s a beautiful painting. You should hang _______ it - it might be worth a lot of money.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to keep something and not sell it, give it to someone, or get rid of it.  Similar to "to keep a hold of"

fields.text_one: The cafe was a place where students and musicians hung _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to spend a lot of time somewhere or with someone, relaxing and enjoying yourself.”

fields.text_one: - "Shannon still seems to be hung ____ ____ Jeff."  -"Yeah, I guess it’s only been five weeks since they broke up."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be very attracted to someone and not be able to change your feelings about them.

fields.text_one: She said "I'll be there in a minute," and hung ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to end a telephone conversation by putting the part of the telephone that you speak into back in its usual place.

fields.text_one: In 1962 the threat of nuclear war hung ______ the whole world.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something unpleasant hangs over you, it seems likely to happen or is going to happen soon and it makes you feel worried about what will happen.

fields.text_one: Everything hangs ____ the next game. If England lose, they're out of the World Cup.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to depend on the result of something in order to be successful.”

fields.text_one: Just hang ____ there, Mr. Mieuli, things will get better
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to keep trying even when you seem unlikely to succeed at something or the situation is difficult.

fields.text_one: The boat was going up and down, and we were all hanging ____ ____ dear life.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to hang on for dear life means to hang on very tightly, especially because you are very worried that you will fall. Similar to "hold on" or "cling on"

fields.text_one: Is it alright if I have a few friends _______ this evening?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to invite someone to come to your house for a meal, drink, conversation, etc. Similar to “to have around”

fields.text_one: What about tomorrow lunchtime? I haven't anything ______ then.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to have an arrangement to do something. “To have a lot on” means “to be very busy”

fields.text_one: Joe is really upset. He's going to see Mum and have it ____ ____ her right now.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to end a disagreement or a difficult situation by talking to the person who you are angry with and telling them why you are angry.

fields.text_one: I can't see what you have _______ Alex’s friends. They seem nice to me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to dislike or disapprove of someone or something for a particular reason, for example because they have done something wrong in the past.

fields.text_one: Tim’s having you ______, Mary. Don't take any notice of him. He is not really a brain surgeon.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to pretend to someone that something is true when it is not, as a joke.

fields.text_one: We climbed on our horses, and headed ____ the hills.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to travel towards a place.

fields.text_one: As we head _____ the new millennium, we will see considerable changes in medical care.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start a period of time or a situation that is completely new and often difficult.

fields.text_one: Goldman praised his team of attorneys, headed _____ by Daniel Petrocelli.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to  lead an organization, team, or project.

fields.text_one: Talks continued throughout the night in the hope of heading _____ the strike.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to prevent something unpleasant from happening.

fields.text_one: A policeman held out his arms to head them ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to make someone or something change their direction, by blocking their way.

fields.text_one: We were both in London when we heard ______ the accident.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get news or information about something or someone

fields.text_one: Please keep the letters coming, Mike. We so enjoy hearing ____ you.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get a letter or a telephone call from someone.

fields.text_one: -  “Do you know Piers Morrison?"  - "No, never heard _____ him."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to have heard the name of a person, place etc before, so that you recognize it when you hear it again.

fields.text_one: Hear me ____ first, Jane, and then you can say what you think.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to listen to what someone wants to say, without trying to interrupt them.

fields.text_one: Jack offered to walk her home, but she wouldn't hear _____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to refuse to allow something, or refuse to accept someone's offer. Normally:  “won’t / wouldn’t hear of”

fields.text_one: This weird guy hit ____ every woman on our floor in the first week of college.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to talk to someone in a way that shows you think they are sexually attractive.

fields.text_one: The multi-millionaire has already hit _____ by threatening to take the newspaper to court.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to criticize or attack a person or group, especially publicly, because they have criticized or attacked you.

fields.text_one: An angry Hurst hit _____ : "It was the worst match since I took over. Our team got what they deserved."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to criticize something or someone strongly because you disapprove of  them - used especially in news reports.

fields.text_one: Frank took me out to dinner and we really hit it _______ straight away.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if  two or more people hit it off, they like each other as soon as they meet each other and become friends very easily.

fields.text_one: They tried various methods before hitting ____ the right one.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think of an idea or plan, especially one that is successful.

fields.text_one: "I know I've been a bit silly," said Claudia "but please don't hold it ________ me."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to feel angry, upset etc with someone because of something they did in the past, or to have a bad opinion of them because of something about them.

fields.text_one: Many students are held ______  at school by poor reading skills.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to prevent someone or something from developing or making progress.

fields.text_one: Can you hold _____ a moment – she’s just coming.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means (informally): to wait for a short time. It is used especially when, telling someone to wait a minute/moment, etc.

fields.text_one: The Council wants to buy the land, but the owners are holding ______ and refusing to sell.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to prevent change or prevent yourself from being forced to do something.

fields.text_one: Protesters held ______ work on the new road for weeks.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to delay something or someone, so that something takes longer or happens later than planned.

fields.text_one: You'd better keep ______, I don't want you to get my cold.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not go near a person, place, or animal.

fields.text_one: I've honestly no idea what happened - do you think I'd keep anything _____ if I knew?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deliberately not tell someone all that you know about something.

fields.text_one: If I didn't keep ________ the children, they'd never get their homework done.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell someone something or ask them something many times, especially in a way that is annoying or unreasonable.

fields.text_one: Teachers should offer advice to children in hospital on how to keep ______ at school.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to manage to do as much or as well as other people.

fields.text_one: George used to play the piano, but I'm afraid he hasn't kept it _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue to practise a skill or subject that you learned in the past so that you do not forget it.

fields.text_one: I've kept _________ several of my school friends, especially the ones that live near me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to write to, telephone, or meet a friend regularly, so that you do not forget each other.

fields.text_one: "What's the matter?" I asked. "You keep ________ of this," Charlie replied sharply.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not get involved in a situation.

fields.text_one: I tried to keep _____ political subjects to avoid any arguments.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to avoid talking about a particular subject, especially because it might upset someone.  Similar to “to avoid” or “to stay off”

fields.text_one: The album has made almost three million dollars in sales around the world, and people keep _____ buying it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue to do something or go somewhere.

fields.text_one: Young people often do silly things because they want to keep _____ with their friends.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to remain friendly with someone and make them continue to like you.

fields.text_one: You’ve been kicking _______ around the idea of asking Gretsky to join our team.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to discuss an idea with a group of people in an informal way.

fields.text_one: After university, I decided to kick _______ Europe for the summer.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to spend time in a place or travelling around a place, doing whatever you want to do or doing very little.

fields.text_one: Stewart decided to kick ______ and enjoy himself Wednesday afternoon.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to relax.

fields.text_one: For some people it can take several hours before the effects of the drug kick ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start to have an effect or start to work.

fields.text_one: The landlord kicked me _____ out of my apartment as soon as I couldn't pay the rent.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to force someone or something to leave a place, organization, or position of power.

fields.text_one: The football club made an offer for the thirty-five-year-old player, but it was knocked ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to to refuse an offer that someone has made. Similar to “to turn down”

fields.text_one: As Tracey was getting out of her car, a motorcycle nearly knocked her ________.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a vehicle knocks someone down, it hits them so that they fall to the ground and may be injured or killed.  Similar to “to knock over” or “to run over”.

fields.text_one: We could knock ______ this wall and have one large room instead of two.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deliberately destroy and remove a building or a part of a building.

fields.text_one: Knock it _____ , Liz! There’s no reason to drive like an idiot!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used to tell someone to stop doing something that is annoying you. Similar to: stop it!, cut it out!

fields.text_one: Louis knocked ______ his opponent in the first round by hitting him square on the jaw.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone become unconscious, for example by hitting them in a fight of giving them drugs.

fields.text_one: When I got home my wife started laying _____ me because I'd forgotten it was our wedding anniversary.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to criticize someone or something very strongly, especially in a way that seems unreasonable or unfair.

fields.text_one: The Geneva Convention lays _______ conditions for the treatment of prisoners of war.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to officially establish a rule or way of doing something, or say officially what someone should do.

fields.text_one: Thousands of workers in the auto and steel industries were laid ______ during the recession of the late 1980s.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop employing a worker because there is not enough work for him or her to do.

fields.text_one: I've already had to lay _____  £500 for the course fees.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to spend money on something, especially a large amount of money. Similar to “to shell out” or “to fork out” (both informal).

fields.text_one: The palace gardens are laid _____ in the same style as the ones at Versailles.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to arrange or plan the way something is organized.. Use this especially about a building, town, or garden, or the design of a book, magazine, etc.

fields.text_one: The boy’s mother has tried to stop him stealing, but she’s convinced it’s older boys who lead him _______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to encourage someone to do bad things that they would not normally do.

fields.text_one: He led her ______ right until the last minute: the wedding was arranged, all the guests were at the church, and he didn't turn up!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deceive someone by telling them things that are not true, especially by making them believe that you love them.

fields.text_one: San Francisco will take on a festival atmosphere in the weeks leading _____ ____ up to the Super Bowl.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a series of events or days, weeks etc lead up to an important event, they come before it.

fields.text_one: If a young child has problems with language, this may lead _____ _____ additional difficulties at school.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to cause something to develop or make it possible for someone to do something at a later time.

fields.text_one: Air-traffic controllers are worried that these proposals could lead _______ a major accident.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to cause something to happen, especially some time later.

fields.text_one: I think I left my credit card _____ at the restaurant.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not take something or someone with you when you leave or go to a place, either because you forgot to take them or because you left them there deliberately.

fields.text_one: Leave _______, Sethe - you're hurting me!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell someone to stop doing something, especially when they are annoying you.

fields.text_one: "I love you, I didn't mean to hurt you." "Oh, leave it _____, Mick- I've heard it all before!"
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used to tell someone that you do not believe what they have just said. Similar to “to come off”

fields.text_one: "What colour shall we paint this room?" "I'll leave that ____ ____ you," Jasper said.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to let someone decide and be responsible for something without trying to influence them.

fields.text_one: You've left _____ a zero in this phone number.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: not to include someone or something, either deliberately or accidentally.

fields.text_one: The builder promised that he’d come today, but he's let me ______ again.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to fail to do something that someone is relying on you to do, in a way that is disappointing or annoying.

fields.text_one: Rooney should have been booked for that foul, but the referee let him ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not punish someone when they have done something wrong.

fields.text_one: Ask the taxi driver to let you _____ by the post office.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to stop a car, bus etc to allow someone to get out. Similar to: “to drop off” (informal) or “to set down”.

fields.text_one: Carol's living with her boyfriend now, but don't let _____ _____ Mum, will you?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you don't let on about a secret or about your feelings, you do not tell other people about them.

fields.text_one: Eugene let ______ a long loud laugh when he heard what had happened.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make a particular sound.

fields.text_one: The security guard refused to let me _______ the gate.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to allow someone or something to pass through and get somewhere.

fields.text_one: I'll drive you into town as soon as the snow lets ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if bad weather or an unpleasant situation lets up, it stops or becomes less serious than before.

fields.text_one: Little kids ask questions all the time. They won't let ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop doing something or to do it less than before, especially when you have been doing it continuously in a very determined way or in a way that annoys someone.

fields.text_one: Kaelin was let _____ _____ his radio contract in order to pursue film and TV roles.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to allow someone not to have to do what they have agreed to do in a contract.

fields.text_one: "Stop the car and let me _____!" Elly screamed.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to allow someone to leave somewhere.

fields.text_one: A great future lies _____ for this talented twenty-three-year-old girl.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a particular situation or problem lies ahead, this is what will happen or what someone will experience in the future.

fields.text_one: It's not a good idea to leave so much money lying _______ the house.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something is lying around, someone has left it carelessly in a place where it should not be.

fields.text_one: He felt so tired that he went straight upstairs and lay ______ on his bed.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to move into a position in which your body is flat, usually in order to sleep or rest.

fields.text_one: Don't wake me up tomorrow morning. I'm going to lie _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay in bed in the morning later than usual, in order to have a rest.

fields.text_one: The fault lies ______ the school for not informing the parents that there was a problem.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something such as a fault, decision, or responsibility lies with someone, it is their fault, decision, responsibility etc, and they are responsible for dealing with it.

fields.text_one: The next morning I woke up and remembered what I’d done. How could I ever live it _______?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you say that someone will not live something down, you mean that they will never make people forget about something silly or embarrassing that they have done.

fields.text_one: All through the football season, I lived _____ Saturdays.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you live for something or someone, they are so important to you that you feel they are your main reason for living.

fields.text_one: Does your nanny live _____?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if someone who is employed in a house or school lives in, they live at the place where they work.

fields.text_one: She can't go on living ____ her parents forever.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get the money that you need to live from someone else, especially when you do not do any work yourself.

fields.text_one: My brother always liked living it _____ at expensive hotels and nightclubs.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to spend time doing exciting and enjoyable things, especially things that cost a lot of money.

fields.text_one: Patissier lived _____  _____ her reputation, and easily won the women’s event.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be as good as people expect or hope.

fields.text_one: At that time we were living ____ $50 a week.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you live on a particular amount of money, you have that amount of money available to buy the things you need to live.

fields.text_one: Great music lives ______ - long after the composer is dead.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to  continue to exist or live, especially for a long time or for longer than expected.

fields.text_one: Clare lives ____ the philosophy that you can do anything if you are determined enough.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to follow carefully particular rules or beliefs that guide or affect your behaviour.

fields.text_one: My grandfather lived ______ two World Wars.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to experience a very difficult situation or event, often one that continues for a long time.

fields.text_one: The governor argued that tougher laws and locking ______ criminals had helped to lower the crime rate.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to put or keep someone in prison, or in a hospital for people who are mentally ill.

fields.text_one: The singer has now locked herself _______ in her Florida home and is refusing to speak to the press.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go somewhere in order to be quiet or get away from other people.

fields.text_one: The guard locked him ____, then sat down outside the door.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to prevent someone from leaving a room or building by locking the door.

fields.text_one: I always leave a spare key with our neighbours now, in case we lock ourselves ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave your keys inside a building, room, car etc by mistake, with the result that you cannot get back inside it after the door has shut.

fields.text_one: The couple, now divorced, are locked _____ a long battle over their children.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be involved in an argument, fight etc with someone, especially one that it is difficult to get out of.

fields.text_one: Her husband looks _______ the children  while she's at work.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to spend time with someone and make sure that they are safe and have the things they need, especially a child or someone who is sick.

fields.text_one: It's important to look _______ and make sufficient provision financially for your retirement.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think about what will happen in the future so that you can make plans or talk about what is likely to happen.

fields.text_one: They spent the morning looking ________ the old part of the city.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to walk around a place looking at the various things there.

fields.text_one: When the old man asked her for money she just looked _______ and ignored him.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to turn your eyes away from someone or something so that you cannot see them.

fields.text_one: Looking _______, I wish I hadn't said some of those things. I must have seemed incredibly rude.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think or remember a situation that happened in the past.

fields.text_one: The problem for old people is often that they have nothing much left to look ____  ____ in their lives.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be excited and happy about something good that is going to happen and think about it a lot.

fields.text_one: I thought I'd look ____  ____ Michael on my way home.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to visit someone for a short time, usually when you are going somewhere else, especially to find out if they are all right.

fields.text_one: A special committee was appointed to look ____ allegations of public corruption following the Watergate affair.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to find out the facts about something such as a crime, a problem, or an accident, so that it can be dealt with.

fields.text_one: Reporters looked _____ in horror as the man was dragged away and beaten to death.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to watch something while it is happening but not take part in it or try to stop it. Similar to “to watch”.

fields.text_one: We've always looked _____ Jack as one of the family.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to consider someone or something in a particular way, or as a particular kind of person or thing.

fields.text_one: Look ______! There’s a train coming!
fields.explanation: Use this phrasal verb to warn someone that they are in danger and that they must do something to avoid it.

fields.text_one: We were a close group of friends, and we all looked ____  ____  each other.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to do what is best for someone, protect them, and make sure that they have as many advantages as possible.

fields.text_one: The player I used to look ____  ____ when I was younger was John McEnroe.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to admire or respect someone a lot, for example because they are older than you and have a lot of experience or knowledge.

fields.text_one: If you don't know what the word means, look it _____ in a dictionary.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to find information about something in a book, in a list, in computer records, etc.

fields.text_one: Adam always felt that we looked ____  ____ him because he hadn't been to university.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think you are better than someone else, for example because you are more successful, or of a higher social class than they are.

fields.text_one: I'm sorry I haven't seen you much lately, but I'll make it ____  ____ you, I promise.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to do something good for someone after disappointing them or treating them badly, so that they forgive you.

fields.text_one: At last the film finished and we got up and made _____ the exit.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: when a lot of people  move towards something at the same time.

fields.text_one: Although the father had made ____  ____ his daughter, there was still a strain between him and his son-in-law.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if two people who have had an argument make up, they talk to each other and agree to become friends again.

fields.text_one: A couple of teenagers were making _____ in the back of the movie theatre.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to kiss and touch someone in a sexual way.

fields.text_one: He couldn't remember any fairy stories, so he made one _____ about a magic carpet - the children loved it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think of something new using your imagination. For example the words for a new song, story, etc.    Note: it is also used in a more negative context, meaning to lie.

fields.text_one: Thieves made _____  _____  thousands of dollars worth of jewellery.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to steal something and escape with it.

fields.text_one: Women made ____ over 40% of the workforce.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if a number of parts or members make up something, they combine together to form it.

fields.text_one: "I say, what do you make _____ this? "Martin said, pointing to a small article in that morning's paper.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if you ask someone what they make of something or someone, you want to know what their opinion of or reaction to them is.

fields.text_one: Janine took the morning off and told her boss that she'll make it ____ later.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if you make up time that you have taken off work, you spend that time working later.

fields.text_one: In the semi-darkness, Delaney could just make _____ the Russian’s face.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if you can make something out, you can see or hear it, but with difficulty.

fields.text_one: -  "How did the exam go?"   - "Terrible. I think I really messed it _____."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make a mistake or do something badly.

fields.text_one: She always told her kids never to mess ______ drugs.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get involved with something or someone that may cause problems or be dangerous. Similar to “to fool about with.”

fields.text_one: I came home to find Mike messing _____  _____ the television.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to change something in order to try to improve it or make It work better, especially when it would be better If you did not.

fields.text_one: I used to mess _____ a lot in class when I was at school.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to behave in a silly way, when you should be working or helping someone.

fields.text_one: Linda is upset because some guy's been messing her _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to treat someone badly, for example by not being completely honest with them or by not doing what you have agreed to do.

fields.text_one: The world has moved ____ since Noel Coward wrote his plays. and some of the ideas seem ridiculously old-fashioned.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if people, ideas, methods etc move on, they become more modern or more advanced. Similar to “to progress”.

fields.text_one: “Move _____, folks, move _____ there, please.” A policeman was now at the stage door, trying to get the crowd to leave.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you are asked to move along, or is someone moves you along, you are asked to leave a particular place and go somewhere else.

fields.text_one: When Anna was nine the family moved ______, and the children faced a strange school and strange people.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave the place where you live and go to live in a different area.

fields.text_one: My parents helped us to buy furniture and carpets and things when we first moved ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin living in a new house or apartment.

fields.text_one: "Actually, " Rosemary whispered, "my husband has moved _____. I don't know where he is."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop living in a particular house, apartment or area, and go to live somewhere else.

fields.text_one: Write your name on this list then pass it _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to give something to one person in a group for them to give to the next person, until everyone has had it. Similar to “to pass on/round”.

fields.text_one: The Mitchell brothers could easily pass ____ twins.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make other people think you are a type of person that you are not, because you look or seem so much like that type.

fields.text_one: The people of the village perform musical dramas which have been passed _____ through the generations.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to give or teach something to people who are younger than you or live after you.

fields.text_one: My mother lived in a remote village, and all the excitement of the 1960s passed her _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if an event passes you by, it happens without your noticing it much or being affected by it.

fields.text_one: John Hewitt had been ill for some time, and passed ____ peacefully on 12th April.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to die - use this when you want to be very polite and avoid using the word “die”. Similar to “to die” or to “pass on”.

fields.text_one: $6 million of prize money is paid _____ every week in the national lottery.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to pay money to someone because they are owed it, or have earned it, or won it.

fields.text_one: I've lost my credit card. Will I have to pay _______ if someone uses it?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to pay money that you owe, especially when you do not want to.

fields.text_one: The bands dedication and practice finally paid _____ when their single made it to number 1 in the charts.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something that you do pays off, it is successful or worth doing.

fields.text_one: Did you remember to pay that cheque _____?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to put money in your bank account or a savings plan.

fields.text_one: Send me the money for a plane ticket home and I'll pay you ______, okay, Mom?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to give someone the money that you owe them.

fields.text_one: The little girl’s mother laughed and bent down to pick her ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to lift something or someone up, especially with your hands. ”To pick up the phone” means: to lift up the phone so that you can use it.

fields.text_one: Sophie naturally picked ______ the most expensive ring in the whole shop.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to choose one particular thing or person from a group.

fields.text_one: My eyes had got accustomed to the dark, so I could pick _____ shapes about seventy-five yards away.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to succeed in seeing someone or something, even though this is difficult, for example because it is dark or they are a long distance from you. Similar to: to make out.

fields.text_one: While I was in Tokyo I picked ____ quite a bit of Japanese.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to learn how to do something by watching or listening to other people or by practising doing it, rather than by being taught.

fields.text_one: In recent months the economy has started to pick _____ again.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a situation picks up, it starts to improve after a time when there have been a lot of problems - use this especially about a company's business or the economic situation in a country, or even the weather.

fields.text_one: All I seem to do is wash, clean, and pick _____ after the children.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to put things back in the right place and make everything neat and tidy, after someone else has taken things out and left them in the wrong place.

fields.text_one: Children tend to pick ____  ____ your worries and stress, and it s difficult to hide your true feelings from them.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to notice something, especially something that other people do not notice.

fields.text_one: Bridget woke up with some strange man who she'd picked ____ at a party the night before.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start talking to someone who you have never met before in order to have a sexual relationship with them.

fields.text_one: Did you manage to pick _____ any bargains in the sales?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get or buy something, especially something that you find by chance and buy for a low price.

fields.text_one: Marjorie was a shy, quiet girl who was always being picked _____ and bullied by the other kids at school.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to treat one person badly in a way that seems very unfair, for example because they are the weakest or they are different from the other people in the group.

fields.text_one: The conductor suddenly  walked out, but the orchestra played _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue playing a musical instrument, even though something has happened which might have stopped you.

fields.text_one: What the hell do you think you're playing _____ - going out at this time of night?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if you ask what someone is playing at, you want to know what they are doing or why they are doing it, because you are very surprised or annoyed by it.

fields.text_one: I hope you're not playing ______ Jane’s feelings – she’s such a nice person.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to treat someone in a way that is not sincere or fair and is likely to upset them, for example by pretending to love them.

fields.text_one: When I left university, I played _______ the idea of teaching for a while.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to consider an idea or a possibility, but not very seriously.

fields.text_one: Is it alright if I borrow your car – my Renault’s been playing ____ a bit recently.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a machine, an electrical system or even a part of your body plays up, it is not working as well as it should.

fields.text_one: I played _____ a bit when I was young, but now I've settled down with one man.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to have a lot of different sexual relationships, or to have a sexual relationship with someone who is not your husband, wife, or usual partner.

fields.text_one: He got home about midnight and played ______ the messages on his answer phone.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to listen to or watch something that has recently been recorded on a tape.

fields.text_one: The government has been trying to play _______ the scandal.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to make people believe that something is less important or serious than it really is.

fields.text_one: At the end of the season, the top two teams will play ______ at Twickenham for the trophy.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if people or teams that have the same number of points play off, they play one last game in a sports competition, in order to decide which one is the winner.

fields.text_one: "It wasn't your fault," Martha said. "You mustn't let it play ____ your mind."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something plays on your mind, you cannot stop thinking about it, and it worries or upsets you.

fields.text_one: He sometimes used to pop ____ for a cup of tea and a chat on her way home.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go into a friend's house, an office, a shop etc for a short time, usually without having arranged your visit. Similar to “to drop in/into” (informal) or “to stop by”.

fields.text_one: New Italian restaurants are popping ____ all over the city.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to appear suddenly in an unexpected way or in unexpected places.

fields.text_one: I'll just pop _____ to Gran's and see if everything's all right.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to someone's house for a short time, usually without having arranged your visit. Similar to “to stop by”.

fields.text_one: "Where's Colin?" "He's just popped _____ to the toilet - he'll be back in a minute."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go out of a room or building quickly, suddenly, or for a short time. Similar to “to nip out” (informal).

fields.text_one: I'm only sixty, you know- I'm not going to pop ______ yet!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to die. Use this when you do not want to say 'die' because it sounds too serious.

fields.text_one: The wine was so bad I just poured it ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get rid of a liquid by pouring it out of its container.

fields.text_one: Letters of complaint poured ____ after the programme was shown.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if letters, phone calls, complaints etc pour in, a lot are received in a short period of time. Similar to “to flood in/into”.

fields.text_one: Mandy was pouring ____ tea and passing around biscuits.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if you pour out a drink, you fill someone's glass, cup, etc. with it.

fields.text_one: Rain poured ____ on Northern California last Friday, decreasing the threat of forest fires.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if the rain pours down, it rains very hard: it's pouring down.

fields.text_one: I finally poured _____ my heart to Michael and told him I'd been in love with him for years.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means:  to tell someone all about your most secret feelings.

fields.text_one: We will press _____ to complete the construction as soon as possible.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue doing something in a determined way, especially when it is difficult.

fields.text_one: If you are pressed _____ time in the mornings, try setting the alarm 30 minutes earlier.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to not have enough time, money, space etc, with the result that it is difficult for you to do something.

fields.text_one: Gorbachev was keen to press ____  ____ modernizing the party.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue doing something in a determined way, even though it is difficult.

fields.text_one: I know you're all tired but I think we should press ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue with your journey, even though it is very difficult.

fields.text_one: Nick kept pressing drinks _____ me all night.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to offer something to someone in a very forceful way, so that it is very difficult for them to refuse to accept it.

fields.text_one: Billy pulled ____ at once, jumped out of the car and offered to help.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if a vehicle pulls over, it moves to the side of the road and it slows down or stops.

fields.text_one: It took Lassiter three years to pull the firm ____ and make it profitable.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: gradually make a business, organization etc begin to be more successful after it has been failing.

fields.text_one: Both the boys have serious injuries, but we're confident that they'll pull _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to succeed in staying alive and gradually get better after you have been seriously ill or injured.

fields.text_one: I want everyone in the department to pull _____ as a team - support each other.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if a group of people pull together, they all work together in order to achieve an aim that they share.

fields.text_one: Quite a lot of the better restaurants will pull you _____ if you're not wearing a tie.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell someone that they have done something wrong, or that they must try to improve in some way.

fields.text_one: The conflicting demands of career and family were pulling her _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone feel very upset and confused. Similar to “to tear apart”.

fields.text_one: The two swam neck and neck for over half the race, before Akers suddenly pulled ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to succeed in getting in front of someone who you are racing against, or in getting more points than a person or team that you are competing against.

fields.text_one: By the time the train pulled ____ King's Cross Station the next day, we were all exhausted.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a train, bus, ship, etc pulls into a place, it arrives there. Similar to “to arrive (at)”.

fields.text_one: This is a difficult role to play, and John Travolta has pulled it ____ magnificently.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to succeed in doing or achieving something difficult.

fields.text_one: The British tennis player, Joe Durie, had to pull ____ with a knee injury.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop doing or being involved in something.

fields.text_one: The start date for the talks has now been pushed ______ to the end of the month.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deliberately delay an event, date, project etc that has already been arranged, usually because people are not ready for it, or other things are more important. Similar to “to put back”, “to put off” or “to postpone”.

fields.text_one: Why do you always let other people push you _____?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell someone what to do in a rude way, especially without considering what they want.

fields.text_one: The improved economy will provide a better climate for workers to push _____ higher wage rates.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: try to persuade people that something should happen or be done.

fields.text_one: At the time I didn't want to stay on at school, but I'm glad my parents pushed me _____ it now.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to force someone to do something that they do not really want to do by being very forceful or using your influence or power.

fields.text_one: Many children feel they have been pushed _____ when a new baby arrives in the family.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to force someone to lose their position by being unpleasant to them or telling them they are no longer needed. Similar to “to squeeze out”.

fields.text_one: Stanley put ____ his newspaper and glared at her.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop holding, carrying, or using something and put it somewhere.

fields.text_one: The girl sitting next to me managed to put ____ half a bottle of vodka before we got to Hong Kong.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to eat or drink a lot of something, especially a surprisingly large amount.

fields.text_one: The meeting has been put ____ to 3 o'clock. I hope you don't mind.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to arrange for something to happen at a later time or date than was planned.

fields.text_one: Her parents used to put ____ a little money each month so that they could pay for her college fees.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to save money, especially regularly, so that you can use it for a particular purpose later.

fields.text_one: Of course foxes aren't pests. That is just an idea that is put _____ by people who support fox hunting.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell people that something is true so that a lot of people believe it, especially something that is not true or not certain.

fields.text_one: A number of theories were put _____ at the time about the possible causes of his death
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to suggest an idea, explanation, plan, etc. for other people to consider and discuss.

fields.text_one: Women are twice as likely as men to get skin cancer. Experts put this ____  ____ the fact that we're more fond of sunbathing.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think that something, especially a problem or a bad situation, is caused by something else.Similar “to attribute to”

fields.text_one: Our cat got cancer, and we had to have him put ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to kill an animal without causing it any pain, because it is old or ill.

fields.text_one: Her ex-husband was always putting her _____ in front of her friends.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to criticize someone in an unkind way that makes them seem stupid or unimportant, when other people are present.

fields.text_one: After the trial, Lopez said he just wanted to put the whole thing  _____ him and get on with the rest of his life.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you put something behind you, especially an unpleasant experience, you forget about it and do not let it affect you in the future.

fields.text_one: When Lesley asked to speak to the manager, she was put ____  ____ the manager’s personal assistant instead.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to connect someone to the person they want to speak to, on the telephone.

fields.text_one: Don't forget to put the lights ____ before you leave the building.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: make a light stop working by pressing or turning a switch.

fields.text_one: He felt he had already put himself _____ by agreeing to see Dougal at such short notice.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to use a lot of effort or time in order to help someone, when this is not convenient for you.

fields.text_one: McEnroe complained that the photographers were putting him _____ his game.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make it difficult for someone to pay attention to what they are doing, for example by talking or making a noise.

fields.text_one: Her husband has decided to put ___ for early retirement.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make an official request to be allowed to do something or have something. Similar to “to apply (for)”.

fields.text_one: Some friends have offered to put us ____ for the night.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to provide someone with a place to stay, usually for a short time.

fields.text_one: Ford has announced plans to put ____ car prices by as much as 5%.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to increase something, for example prices, taxes, or rents.

fields.text_one: The same question was put ___ thousands of Americans. ‘Are you, or have you ever been, a member of the Communist Party?"
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to ask someone a question, especially officially and about something important.

fields.text_one: The band put ____ a string of hit records in the early sixties.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to produce a record, book, or other product and make it available for people to buy.

fields.text_one: I  must have put my mother ____ hell when I was a teenager.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone do something difficult or experience something unpleasant.

fields.text_one: Men do have some uses - putting ______ shelves for instance.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to attach a shelf, cupboard etc to a wall.

fields.text_one: Kate felt put ____. Why was she always the one who had to stay at home with the kids while William was out enjoying himself?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if someone feels put upon, they feel that they are being treated unfairly, especially because they are expected to do more work than other people.

fields.text_one: “Has Candy put you ____  ____ this?" Rory demanded. “You are normally such a well-behaved Child to it.”
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to encourage someone to do something stupid or dangerous, especially when this is very different from how they usually behave.

fields.text_one: The police have to put ____  ____ a lot of abuse.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to accept an unpleasant situation or someone's annoying behaviour without complaining.

fields.text_one: She says that if she wins, she's going to put it ____ a trip to Italy.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to use some money in order to pay part of the cost of something.

fields.text_one: It's often a good idea to get someone else to read ____ your essay before you hand it in.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to read something carefully in order to check details or find mistakes. Similar to “to read through”.

fields.text_one: When I read ______ what I had written, I was quite pleased with it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to read something that you have written, to check that it is correct and satisfactory.

fields.text_one: He opened the envelope and read ____ the name of the winner.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to read something and say the words, especially the words or numbers that are written in a list, message etc, so that other people can hear them.

fields.text_one: Robert wondered if she was reading more ____ his comments than he actually meant.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think that something has a meaning or importance that it may not really have.

fields.text_one: I'll have to read ____  ____ the tax laws before that meeting tomorrow.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to read about a particular subject, because you want to know more about it.

fields.text_one: Are they aware that their songs are being ripped ____ and copied by bands in other countries?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to steal someone else's idea by copying something that they have made or invented, especially in order to sell it.

fields.text_one: The explosion of three massive bombs which ripped ____ the heart of the city
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a storm, an explosion, or bullets rip through something, they go through it very quickly and violently causing a lot of damage.

fields.text_one: A lot of the taxi drivers here will try and rip you ____ if they think you're a tourist.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to cheat someone by making them pay much more than the usual price for  something.

fields.text_one: She ripped ____ Tom’s photograph and threw it on the fire.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tear something quickly and violently into small pieces, especially something made of paper or cloth.

fields.text_one: What is wrong with old Moreton? He ripped _____ me just now for being two minutes late.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to talk to someone angrily and criticize them very strongly for doing something.

fields.text_one: It was after midnight when he finally rolled ____. He hadn't even bothered to phone us.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if someone rolls in, they arrive somewhere later than they should, and often they do not seem to care about being late.

fields.text_one: Derringer owns a mansion in Beverly Hills, so he must be rolling ____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to be very rich.

fields.text_one: L'Oreal rolled ____ a line of skin-care products called Plenitude.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make a new product available for people to buy or use. Similar to “to introduce” or “to launch”.

fields.text_one: She rolled ______ and went back to sleep.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to turn your body when you are lying down, so that you are lying on the other side of your body.

fields.text_one: Just roll _____ the carpet and take it downstairs.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make something made of paper, cloth etc into the shape of a tube or ball, by folding it over several times.

fields.text_one: Use an electric sander to round _____ the corners.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you round off the sharp edges or corners of an object, you make them smooth and round by rubbing them with a special tool.

fields.text_one: The total came to $299.50, so I rounded it ___  ___ $300.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to increase an exact number to the nearest higher whole number, or the nearest 10, 100 etc above it.

fields.text_one: Fresh strawberries will round the meal ____ nicely.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be a pleasant and suitable way of ending an event, or to do something as a pleasant and suitable way of ending it.

fields.text_one: See if you can round ____ a few friends to help you.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to find and gather a group of people or animals together.

fields.text_one: Harry got up out of his seat in a flash and rounded ____ the man: "Don't dare to speak to me that way. If you insult me again I'll punch your fat head.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to suddenly attack someone when they do not expect it, either physically or by speaking angrily to them.

fields.text_one: Do it in pencil first then you can rub it ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to remove writing or pictures from paper by rubbing it with a piece of rubber, or remove writing or pictures from a board by rubbing it with a cloth.

fields.text_one: Always keep hand cream available in the bathroom or kitchen and rub it ____ frequently.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to put a cream or oil onto someone's skin, hair etc and rub it in order to make it go into their skin, hair, etc.

fields.text_one: After a brief shower and a rub-_____ with a face cloth and towel, I was feeling refreshed.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to dry a person or animal by rubbing them with a towel (a piece of cloth used for drying your skin). A rub-down (noun) is when you dry yourself with a towel.

fields.text_one: - "Remember, while you're unemployed, I have to pay for everything.“  - “All right, there's no need to rub it _____."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deliberately remind someone about a fact that they want to forget because they are upset or  embarrassed about it. E.g. don't rub it in!

fields.text_one: He competes so hard, it rubs ____  ____ the rest of the team and makes them better.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if someone else's quality, feeling, or habit rubs off on you, you start to have it too because you are with that person.

fields.text_one: Hartwig ran ____ the names in the notebook to see if there were any that he recognized.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to quickly read or look at something, especially in order to check or find something.

fields.text_one: Lee was really upset when her cat got run ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to drive over someone or something, especially with the result that they are injured or killed.

fields.text_one: His wife ran ____ and left him.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to suddenly leave someone or leave the place where you live, without telling anyone.

fields.text_one: My dad will run ____ for hours about golf if you give him the chance.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to talk for a long time, especially when other people are not interested in what you are talking about.

fields.text_one: While I was in Paris I ran _____ an old school friend who I hadn't seen in years.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to meet someone you know by chance, when you did not expect to meet them. Similar to “to pump into”, “to run across” or “to come across”.

fields.text_one: Is Sue all right? She looked rather run _____ when I last saw her and in need of a vacation.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to feel tired and unhealthy because you have been working too hard, not getting enough sleep, or worrying a lot about something.

fields.text_one: Run _____ now children! It's time you were in bed!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell a child to go away.

fields.text_one: Sorry, I was thinking about something else. Can you run that one ____ me again?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to say something again to someone, in order to make sure they have understood it.

fields.text_one: Burns wants to run ____ governor at the next election.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to be elected to a particular position.

fields.text_one: The company had run ____ financial difficulties during the recession.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you run into problems, difficulties etc, you suddenly experience them and have to deal with them, especially when you did not expect them.

fields.text_one: Di and Dodi were killed when their car ran ____ a wall at high speed in Paris.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to accidentally drive into something such as a car or a wall.” Similar to “to drive (into)”.

fields.text_one: Their adventure lasted until the money ran ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something runs out, there is no more of it left.

fields.text_one: We should be through by eight, but the session might run ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a meeting, game, television programme etc runs over, it continues past the time when it was planned to end.

fields.text_one: I think we'll start by running ____ the opening dance routine.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to quickly do a series of things, especially in order to practise them.

fields.text_one: The Rome Opera company has run ____ debts of over $40 million.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to run up debts, losses, a bill, a deficit, a tab, etc. to borrow or lose a lot of money, or have to pay a big bill for something.

fields.text_one: My best friend Judy came to the airport to see me ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to the airport, train station etc to say goodbye to someone who is leaving. Similar to “to wave off” or “to say goodbye to somebody”.

fields.text_one: Klein shook Carson’s hand and saw him _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to show a visitor the way to leave by walking there with them. E.g: I'll see myself out spoken (used to tell someone they do not have to come to the door with you).

fields.text_one: It’s a difficult job, but I'm going to see it _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue to do something until it finishes, even if it is difficult or you do not like doing it.

fields.text_one: Eventually I saw _____ her lies and ended the relationship.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you see through someone or what they are saying, you realize that they are trying to influence you or deceive you.

fields.text_one: - "These papers need filing."  - "Don't worry, I'll see _____ that."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deal with something or make sure it happens.

fields.text_one: The principal of Bonham High impressed her so much that she was sold ____ the school.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to like or support something, especially an idea or plan.

fields.text_one: The company plans to sell _____ its budget hotels and concentrate on upgrading its restaurants.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sell all or part of an industry or company.

fields.text_one: Most music stores have already sold ____  ____ Ice Cube’s new rap album.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a shop sells out of something, it has no more of that particular thing left to sell.

fields.text_one: Mitch sold ____, trading a lot of dreams for a bigger paycheck.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to do something that is against your beliefs or principles in order to get power, money, etc.

fields.text_one: Rosa wanted Mum to sell ____ and go and live in Rome.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sell your house or business so that you can go somewhere else or do something else.

fields.text_one: Harry Enfield sends _____ Tony Blair brilliantly in his new comedy series.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone or something seem silly by copying them in a funny way.

fields.text_one: He was found guilty of armed robbery and sent _____ for six years.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to put someone in prison.

fields.text_one: Police were sent _____ to break up the fight between football fans.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to send soldiers, police etc somewhere to deal with a dangerous situation.

fields.text_one: I think I'll send the sweater _____. It just doesn't fit right.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to return something, usually by mail, to the company or shop where it came from because you do not like or need it, or because it is broken.

fields.text_one: My coach recommended many years ago that I send ____  ____ the Charles Atlas exercise manual.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to send a letter to a company or organization asking them to send something to you.

fields.text_one: They settled in the United States after the war and quietly set _____ rebuilding their lives, putting the past behind them.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start doing something, especially something that needs a lot of time and effort set about doing something.

fields.text_one: The Challenger disaster not only cost the lives of seven astronauts, but also set _____ the nation’s space program for years.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to delay the progress or development of something. Similar to “to hold up”, “to put back” or “to delay”.

fields.text_one: I wanted to set _____ early to avoid the traffic.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start to go somewhere. Similar to “to set out”.

fields.text_one: They want to set _____ their own import-export business
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start a business or organization.

fields.text_one: What made you change your mind? Last night, you were dead set ____ the idea.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to to be strongly opposed to something. Similar to “to be opposed to”.

fields.text_one: As winter sets _____, we can see a worrying increase in the number of young homeless people on our streets.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if the rain, the winter, or a difficult period sets in, it begins and seems likely to continue.

fields.text_one: Don't mention anything about weddings - you'll only set her _____ again.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone start crying, laughing, or talking about something that they often talk about.

fields.text_one: The driver set her _____ at the station.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if the driver of a bus, taxi, or train sets you down somewhere, he or she stops there and lets you get out.  Similar to “to drop off” (informal).

fields.text_one: Try to set _____ at least an hour each day for learning new vocabulary.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to keep something, especially time or money, for a special purpose, and only use it for that purpose.

fields.text_one: Put that cigarette out you idiot - you'll set the smoke detector _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make something such as an alarm system start operating, especially when this was not intended. Similar to “to trigger off” or “to activate”.

fields.text_one: - "How did you meet your husband?"  - ''A friend set us _____."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to arrange for two people to meet because you think they will be attracted to each other.

fields.text_one: Sam Reed scored twice and then set _____ the third goal for Tom Cox.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to pass the ball to another player so that they can get a goal or a point.

fields.text_one: The four suspects claimed they had been set _____ by the police.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deliberately make people think that someone has done something wrong or illegal when they have not.

fields.text_one: I've achieved what I set ______ to achieve - I'm ready for a new challenge now.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start doing something, or making plans to do something, in order to achieve a particular result.

fields.text_one: Columbus set _____ from Europe to discover a new route for the spice trade from the Orient.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start a journey, especially a long journey.

fields.text_one: They want $2500 for it, but they might settle ____ $2000.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to accept something even though it is not the best, or not what you really want.

fields.text_one: I’ve settled ____ and checked out of the hotel.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to pay what you owe on an account or bill.

fields.text_one: I don't feel ready to settle ____ and commit myself to a relationship yet.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start living in a place with the intention of staying there, often with a husband or wife, and especially after you have travelled a lot or had other lovers.

fields.text_one: They haven't settled ____ a name for the baby yet.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if two or more people settle on something they agree to choose it, especially after discussing all the possibilities and thinking about it for a long time.

fields.text_one: How do you like your new home? Are you settling ____ OK?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin to feel happy and relaxed in a new situation, home, job, or school.

fields.text_one: I waited on the steps for about five minutes before somebody finally opened the door and showed me _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to lead someone who is visiting into a room or a building, especially in order for them to meet someone there. Similar to “to see in/into”. Opposite verb: “to show out”.

fields.text_one: A representative had arranged to meet us at the house that afternoon and show us _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go around a place with someone to show them what is interesting or what they need to know. Similar to “to show over”.

fields.text_one: I can't stand the way she shows _____ in front of the other students.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to make other people admire you, by behaving in a way that you think makes you seem intelligent, skilful, or rich, but in fact is just annoying or silly.

fields.text_one: The administration had lost control of the situation and had been shown _____ as useless.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to show that someone or something is bad, unpleasant etc, especially when it was not clear before.

fields.text_one: We spent half an hour waiting for Martin to show _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to  arrive, especially at a place where people are expecting you. Similar to “to turn up” or “to pitch up”.

fields.text_one: In 1982 a series of strikes led to the airline being shut _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a business, factory, shop etc is shut down or shuts down, it closes and stops working for a long time or permanently. Similar to “to close down”.

fields.text_one: I often had to shut myself _____ until two or three in the morning in order to get the work done.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to keep away from other people, for example by going to a quiet room or staying at home, especially for long periods.
