fields.text_one: I tried to see him several times, but he shut me ____ by slamming the door in my face.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to prevent someone from entering a place, especially by closing a door.

fields.text_one: Mr Barnaby was just shutting _____ his shop in East London, when a gang of four armed men burst in.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to close and lock a house, shop, room etc that you own, temporarily, so that people cannot get into it or use it. Similar to “to close up”.

fields.text_one: When we left college there were so few teaching jobs available that a lot of us had to sign ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to claim the money given by the government to people without employment, because you do not have a job.

fields.text_one: How many people have signed ____ to go on the theatre trip so far?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to take part in an activity or a course of study, by writing your name down on a form or list.

fields.text_one: It was 8:58 pm and I'd been working hard all day so I decided it was time to sign ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to finish doing something, especially after you have been doing it for a long time.

fields.text_one: For security reasons, the company requires all visitors to sign ____ at reception.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to write your name in a book when you arrive somewhere that you are visiting, for example a hotel or an office. Opposite to “to sign out”.

fields.text_one: When Julie and her husband split after ten years of marriage, he signed ____ everything in the house to her.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to give property or a legal right to someone else, by signing an official document. Similar to “to sign away”.

fields.text_one: Kosar sat _____ two games of the 1990 season because of a broken thumb.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not take part in a game, competition, dance ere, because you are injured or tired.

fields.text_one: Do you mind if I just sit _____ today? I'm not feeling very well.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be present at a class, meeting, discussion, etc but only watch or listen instead of taking part.

fields.text_one: Yvonne will be sitting ____  ____ me tomorrow while I'm at the conference.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to a meeting, do a job etc instead of the person who usually does it.

fields.text_one: “I am willing to sit ____  ____ the Mexican leaders to discuss Fee trade,” Boice said.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to solve a problem, or to deal with something that needs to be done, by giving it all your attention.

fields.text_one: We had to sit _____ a whole day of boring talks about the company.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay at a meeting, performance etc until it finishes, even though it is very long or boring.

fields.text_one: People are starting to sit ____ and take notice about the dangers of genetically modified foods.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to suddenly start paying attention to someone or something.

fields.text_one: They sat _____ late into the night talking about old times.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay awake and not go to bed. Similar to “to stay up”.

fields.text_one: Just sit ____ and read the paper, I'll make dinner tonight.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get into a comfortable position and relax.

fields.text_one: Adrianne sat ____ the letter for a few days, unsure if she should mail it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be very slow at dealing with something, or to delay dealing with something because you have not decided what you want to do.

fields.text_one: Would you just sit ____ if it were your husband having an affair?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to allow something to happen when you should be doing something to try to stop it. Similar to “to stand by”.

fields.text_one: There's no hurry. I'm going to sleep ____ it, and tomorrow I'll decide what to do.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to delay making a decision about something until the next day or later.

fields.text_one: I suppose they're sleeping _____ the effects of last night's party.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sleep until you do not feel ill any more, especially after drinking too much alcohol.

fields.text_one: We usually sleep ____ on Sunday mornings as it is the only day that we don’t have to get up early.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sleep later than usual in the morning, especially because you do not have to go to work or school. Similar to “to lie in”

fields.text_one: A guy who's spent his youth sleeping _____ isn't going to find it easy to settle down to married life.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to have sex with a lot of different people without having a serious relationship with any of them.

fields.text_one: Mum, it is late and I have had a few drinks. Is it okay if I sleep _____ at Jim's place tonight?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sleep at someone else's house for a night.

fields.text_one: Timothy Gedge had let the truth slip _____ while he was drunk.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if a remark or a piece of information slips out, you mention it without intending to.

fields.text_one: As the game went on I could feel our chances of winning the  championship slipping _____ from us.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means someone's power or their chance of success slips away, it gradually disappears.  Also means to die

fields.text_one: It was a serious lecture, but I was tempted to slip _____ a joke about the Clinton affair.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to quickly mention something when you are talking or writing about something else, without emphasizing it or saying much about it.

fields.text_one: She slipped ____  ____ her swimsuit and wrapped a towel around her.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to take off clothes or shoes quickly.

fields.text_one: Unless Manchester United slip ____ badly, they're sure to win the European Cup
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make a careless mistake, especially when you are doing your job or playing a game.

fields.text_one: "We're here standing ____  ____ freedom against our oppressors" one demonstrator declared.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to support or defend a person, idea, or principle when they are being attacked or criticized.

fields.text_one: There are some interesting paintings in the exhibition, but one artist's work really stands ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be clearly better than other similar things or people.

fields.text_one: Schools are working with a network called SHAPE, which stands ____ 'Shaping Health As Partners in Education'.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to represent a word, phrase, or idea.

fields.text_one: Kate and Louie agreed to stand ____ their son Matt as he recovered from his drug addiction.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay loyal to something, or to continue to give someone help and support when they are in a difficult situation.

fields.text_one: There are lots of young men standing _____ on street corners, obviously without a job to go to.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stand somewhere and not do anything. Similar to “to loiter”.

fields.text_one: How sad for a child to start ____ in life with such a cruel father and a weak mother!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin your life or career in a particular way.

fields.text_one: After yelling at me for leaving the kitchen a mess, Mom started ____ Gary for coming home late.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin criticizing someone or complaining to someone about something. Similar to “to lay into” (informal).

fields.text_one: Arthur got into the car and started it _____ without any problems.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to if you start up an engine, car, machine etc, or it starts up, it begins to work.

fields.text_one: We started ____ at 10 0 'clock in the morning, and reached Ambleside by 5 pm.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin to go somewhere. Similar to “to set off” or “to set out”.

fields.text_one: "I didn't start _____ to be a model," says Yasmin. "I did it once, and then more work just kept coming."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to intend to do something from the beginning. Similar to “to set out”.

fields.text_one: It was Saturday night and we’d decided to stay ____ late and watch the horror movie on TV
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to bed later than usual.

fields.text_one: This is a very unpleasant business, and if I were you I'd stay ____ ____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: not to become involved in a situation, activity, discussion etc.

fields.text_one: If you are expecting a baby, the best advice is to stay _____ alcohol altogether.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not drink, eat, or take something that is bad for you, for example alcohol or drugs.

fields.text_one: Sarah hadn't been out for a long time, preferring to stay _____ and look after Bradley.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to remain at home, especially in the evening. Similar to “to stop in”. Opposite to “to go out”.

fields.text_one: Phil had never stayed ____ without phoning me before, so I was really worried.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not come home at night, or to come home late, especially when someone is expecting you.

fields.text_one: I just stepped ____ to have a cigarette.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go out for a short time.

fields.text_one: In the second half, United stepped ____ the pressure and took the lead.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to increase the amount of effort, pressure etc, or increase the speed of something.

fields.text_one: Gary stepped ____ to calm things down between the boys.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to help or stop the trouble when a situation is difficult or there is an argument.

fields.text_one: If you don't step ____ it, we'll miss the plane!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to hurry and drive faster - used especially when telling someone to drive faster.

fields.text_one: Many people felt that the old King should step ______ and give his son a chance.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave your job or an official position, especially so that someone else can do it instead of you.

fields.text_one: I have some close friends who are prepared to stick ____ me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to support someone when they are in a difficult situation or have problems. Similar to “to stand by” or “to stick up for”.

fields.text_one: If a client doesn't agree with you, you must stick ____  ____ what you believe, but calmly and intelligently.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to defend or fight for something that is important.

fields.text_one: Marcia had said she would help, and she was determined to stick _____ her word.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to do exactly what you have promised to do.

fields.text_one: If you stick ____ for a while, I'm sure you'll find some sort of job.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay in a place, especially because you are waiting for something.

fields.text_one: You'll never be good at  anything unless you stick _____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: continue to work hard at something, even if it is difficult or unpleasant.

fields.text_one: The Foreign Minister will stop _____ in Paris on his way to the conference for talks with French officials.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay somewhere for a night or a few days during a long journey, especially in order to rest or visit someone.

fields.text_one: Lizzie stopped ____ all night on Saturday, my Mum won't let me do the same.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay out late at night at a club, party etc. Similar to “to stay out”.

fields.text_one: I want to stop _____ and see Tracy on the way home.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to visit a person or place for a short time, especially when you are on your way to somewhere else.

fields.text_one: On the way back home, he stopped _____ to look at a house he was thinking of buying.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop during a journey, for example in order to see something or someone, or to have a rest.

fields.text_one: I stopped ____ to watch the baseball and it went on until after twelve.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not go to bed at the normal time and stay up late, especially in order to do something.
